[Comment "short-sweet-the-french-defense/course/25950, variation/4305752"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 {The Advance Variation is a great point to start in the French 
as it faces one of the three major variations in dealing with the tension placed 
on the white center with black's second move: 1) Push locking the center 2) 
Protect e4 3) Exchange away the tension.} 3. e5 {[%csl Rc8,Rc1,Gf1,Gf8] This 
fixing of the pawn structure now clearly defines the Bishops. When evaluating 
the French Bishop (c8-Bishop) we need to define and understand the concept of 
good versus bad A Good Bishop is on the opposite color as its pawns. A Bad 
Bishop is on the same color as its pawns. This is directly applicable to the 
central pawn structure as any endgame with Good Bishop versus Bad Bishop with 
equal pawns will result in a position of playing for two results for the Good 
Bishop wielder. Across nearly all variations in the French we will need to 
handle the issue of our French Bishop.} c5 {[%cal Gc5d4][%csl Rd4] The classical 
and typical Pawn Lever to tear down the pawn wall white has imposed, this is 
seen across every variation we cover when white chooses to lock the center.} 4. 
dxc5 {Poor positional judgement by White. Not only does this help satisfy 
Black's main goal of proving the e5-pawn to be overextended, it also allows 
Black to develop efficiently.} Nc6 {[%cal Gc6e5,Gf8c5][%csl Re5,Rc5]} (4... Bxc5 
{transposes. We are emphasizing the focus on the weak e5-square with this move 
order.}) 5. Nf3 Bxc5 6. Bd3 Qc7 {[%cal Gc7e5,Gc6e5][%csl Re5]} ({It should be 
noted that the strongest move here is} 6... f6 {which is a worthy alternative 
for the reader who enjoys more of a scrap. The setup with ...Qc7 and ...Ne7-g6 
just eschews complications with easy and practical play.}) 7. Qe2 Nge7 {[%cal 
Be7g6,Gg6e5,Gc6e5,Gc7e5][%csl Re5] Black has a harmonious position and White is 
tied down to defense. The e5-pawn will be a point of contention for the 
remainder of the game.} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: The French Defense"]
[Site "Main Level"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Advance Variation -"]
[Black "Course Mainline 7 a4"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "Main Level"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-the-french-defense/course/25950, variation/4305753"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 {The classical and typical Pawn Lever to tear down 
the pawn wall white has imposed, this is seen across every variation we cover 
when white chooses to lock the center.} 4. c3 {[%cal Gc3d4,Gc5d4]} Ne7 {[%cal 
Be7c6] A key move and major Memory Marker for the variation. This initiates the 
overall plan of trading off our Bad Bishop on c8, The French Bishop.} (4... Qb6 
{We also cover in the text this alternative with the idea of playing Bd7 and Bb5 
to rid ourselves of the French Bishop.}) 5. Nf3 Nec6 {[%cal Bb7b6,Ba7a5,Bc8a6] 
Many seeing this variation for the first time get a bit confused...Why are we 
making our Knight go from g8 to c6 when the other Knight can go there in a 
single move? The key to this manouver is the Knight on b8 is needed to protect 
the a6 square to trade off our French Bishop. The c6 Knight will stop the idea 
of Qa4+ which could drop the Bishop on a6 unless we had this move in place.} 6. 
a3 {[%cal Bb2b4] White's typical response in the Advanced Variaiton mainline 
with the plan of playing for b4 which in turn will threaten b5 stopping our idea 
with good effect, so we need prophylaxis against their prophylaxis. In the main 
text we cover multiple moves and plans in this chapter seen across the other 
mentioned moves.} (6. Bd3 b6 7. O-O (7. Qe2 {Attempting to stop ...Ba6, so we 
simply start to back up this threat.} a5 8. a4 cxd4 9. cxd4 Nb4 10. Bb5+ {leaves 
no real issue for Black.}) 7... Ba6 8. Re1 Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Be7 10. Nbd2 O-O {and 
Black is doing fine.}) a5 {Stopping b2-b4 so that we may resume our main idea.} 
7. a4 b6 8. Na3 cxd4 {[%cal Gc6b4][%csl Gb4] White is left with the poor 
decision of allowing the b4 square to be used in the long-term by the Knights.} 
9. cxd4 Be7 10. Nb5 (10. Be2 {should transpose to this variation. We have chosen 
to start with 10. Nb5 as it affords more options to White.}) O-O 11. Be2 Ba6 12. 
O-O Na7 {[%cal Ga7b5,Ga6b5,Bd8d7,Gd7b5][%csl Rb5] We are increasing pressure on 
the b5 square. If White were to move the knight then we would achieve our aim of 
trading light-squared bishops.} 13. Bd2 {A more accurate square than f4 because 
in the ensuing variations it is nice for White to have the option of Bxb4.} Qd7 
14. Qb3 Nbc6 {[%cal Bc6b4,Bf8c8]} 15. Rfc1 {[%cal Gc1c7][%csl Rc7] Stopping us 
from playing ...Nb4 because of the Rc7 threat.} Rfc8 16. Bf1 Nb4 17. Rxc8+ Bxc8 
$10 (17... Rxc8 $6 {is met by} 18. Bxb4 {followed 19. Nd6. After the text Black 
has a solid position.}) *

[Event "Short & Sweet: The French Defense"]
[Site "Main Level"]
