[White "Exchange Variation - 4 Bd3"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "Main Level"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-the-french-defense/course/25950, variation/4305754"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 exd5 {The least invasive of all variations of the 
French and the typical variation that gives most players pause when choosing the 
French as their weapon against 1. e4. Rest assured that if you study the lines 
thoroughly within the main text you will get practical positions which you can 
press for a win with Black. Do not fear lower rated players playing this against 
you.} 4. Bd3 {One of the major variations but there are plenty of alternatives 
that we cover.} (4. Nf3 Bg4 {Setting an imbalance} 5. h3 Bh5 6. Qe2+ Qe7 7. Be3 
Nc6 8. Nc3 O-O-O 9. O-O-O f6 {Not a typical boring Exchange French, Kasparov 
played this with White on occasion.}) (4. Nc3 {Our rule is to set an imbalance 
no matter what 4th move White chooses.} c6 5. Bd3 Bd6 6. Nge2 Qf6 7. Be3 Bf5 
{Trading off the Bad Bishop}) (4. c4 {White is helping change the pawn structure 
into an isolated pawn game with definitive imbalances.} Nf6 5. Nc3 Be7 6. Nf3 
O-O 7. Be2 {A key moment and memory marker forcing White to waste a tempo.} 
dxc4) Nc6 {[%cal Gc6b4,Gc6d4][%csl Rd4,Rd3]} 5. c3 Bd6 {[%cal 
Gd6h2,Bg8e7,Bc8f5][%csl Gd6,Rf4] A common theme of development as the most 
aggressive and optimal square of the Bishop. As we have seen in the videos, the 
good Bishop desires to be on the best square to prevent white's bad Bishop from 
reaching f4. On top of this idea, we need our Knight on e7 to be able to trade 
off our 'French Bishop' on f5. Remember... we are always looking to trade our 
'Bad/French Bishop' for White's 'good Bishop'.} 6. Ne2 {The main idea for White 
is flexibility to attempt to trade off the Bad dark-squared Bishop, Nf3 is 
always answered by ...Bg4 in the main course in order to create a favorable 
imbalance. Our goal overall when playing the Exchange Variation is to create 
favorable imbalances without playing 'copy chess' where we mimic White. When 
copying White's ideas we will always be a step behind, we need to break symmetry 
to try for an edge.} Qf6 {[%cal Gf6f5,Gf6f4][%csl Gf5,Gf4] Stops Bf4 and 
prepares Bf5 the best of both worlds. Black's aim is to get rid of the 'Bad 
Bishop/French Bishop' (light-squared) but doesn't want to trade the Good 
dark-squared Bishop, a theme seen in multiple variations in the Exchange 
French.} 7. Nd2 Bf5 {[%cal Bf5d3]} 8. Nf3 h6 {Not the only move, but it leads to 
a pretty forcing variation.} 9. Bf4 Bxd3 10. Bxd6 Be4 (10... Qxd6 {is also 
equal.}) 11. Bxc7 Bxf3 12. gxf3 Qxf3 13. Rg1 Nge7 14. Rxg7 {Not forced, but we 
have included it to demonstrate that the pawn sacrifice is temporary.} Nf5 15. 
Rg1 Kd7 {[%cal Ba8e8,Ge8e1][%csl Re2,Re1]} 16. Bg3 Rae8 17. Kd2 Ne3 $1 {[%cal 
Be3c4,Be3d1][%csl Rd1]} 18. fxe3 Qxe3+ 19. Kc2 Qxe2+ {Followed by the idea of 
...Rxe2+, ...Na5 and ...Nc4 with pressure.} *

