1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Be7 5. e5 (5. Bxf6 Bxf6 6. Nf3 O-O 7. Bd3 c5 
{.}) {We go more in-depth into all side variations in our full course Master the 
French.} Nfd7 6. h4 (6. Bxe7 Qxe7 {Twelve trainable variations are covered from 
this move in our full course.}) h6 {[%csl Rg5]} 7. Bxe7 (7. Be3 h5 {An 
interesting move which dramatically slows down White's attacking potential on 
the Kingside.}) (7. Qh5 a6 {A necessary move in these variations to stop 
Nb5-counterplay which is necessary here because of the pin on the e7-Bishop. 
Nd6+ would be devastating.} 8. Nf3 c5 {the typical break.}) Qxe7 8. Qg4 {[%csl 
Rg7]} (8. f4 a6 {This is convered in six variations in the full course.}) O-O 9. 
f4 c5 {[%cal Gc5d4][%csl Rd4]} 10. Nf3 {This time White was ready to support the 
center.} Nc6 {[%cal Gc6d4,Gc5d4][%csl Rd4]} 11. O-O-O cxd4 {Beginning a forcing 
variation.} 12. Nxd4 Nxd4 13. Rxd4 f6 {[%cal Bf6e5,Gf8f1,Gd7e5][%csl Re5]} 14. 
exf6 {White's only real option is to take.} Nxf6 15. Qd1 {Not the only square, 
but a reasonable one.} Qc5 {[%cal Gc5d5,Gc5d4][%csl Rd4,Gd5] Adding support to 
d5 so we can respond to White's f4-f5 with ...e5. Black will attack on the 
queenside. Black's dark squared weaknesses are compensated by the attacking 
prospects and this makes the variation viable.} *

