1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. f4 c5 {[%cal Bb8c6,Gc5d4][%csl Rd4]} 
6. Nf3 Be7 7. Be3 O-O 8. Qd2 (8. dxc5 Nxc5 9. Qd2 a6 {.}) b6 {[%cal 
Bd4c5,Bb6c5][%csl Gc5]} 9. O-O-O {Is probably already inaccurate and Black gets 
a serious attack on the queenside.} (9. Nd1 a5 10. c3 a4 11. Bd3 Ba6) (9. Be2) 
(9. h4) Nc6 ({The immediate} 9... c4 {is a possible alternative}) 10. Kb1 {This 
is slow. The response to both this move and Be2 is the same - 10... c4. We are 
following an example game of GM Lenderman.} (10. Bb5 Ndb8 11. f5 cxd4 12. Bxd4 
a6 13. Bxc6 Nxc6 14. Qf2 b5 {.}) c4 {[%cal Ba7a5,Bb6b4]} 11. f5 b5 ({In the stem 
game, GM Lenderman's opponent played} b5 12. fxe6 {, but in the full course we 
also consider the more critical moves} (12. f6) ({and} 12. Nxb5 {.})) 12. fxe6 
{White kills his own counterplay.} (12. f6 gxf6 13. exf6 Bxf6 14. Nxb5 Rb8 15. 
Nc3 Qb6) (12. Nxb5 Rb8 13. Nd6 Bxd6 14. exd6 Nf6 15. Bg5 Qb6) fxe6 13. Nxb5 Rb8 
{[%cal Gb8b2][%csl Rb2,Rb5]} 14. Nd6 Bxd6 15. exd6 Nf6 {[%cal 
Bd8d6,Bf6e4,Bc8d7,Gb8b1,Gc4c3][%csl Rb2,Rb1] With ...Qxd6, ...Bd7 and ...Ne4 to 
follow. Black had a strong attack in: Arenas, D. - Lenderman, A., 0-1, 11th 
American Continental, 2016} *

