1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e5 (4. exd5 exd5 5. Bg5 Be7 6. Bd3 Nc6 {An odd 
move as typically Nc3 is met by ...c6, but we have an extra idea here.} 7. Nge2 
Nb4 8. Bb5+ c6 9. Ba4 O-O 10. O-O h6 11. Bxf6 Bxf6) Nfd7 5. Nf3 (5. Nce2 {In the 
main course 10 variations on Nce2 are covered.}) (5. Qg4 c5 6. Nb5 cxd4 7. Nf3 
Nc6 8. Nd6+ Bxd6 9. Qxg7 Bb4+ 10. c3 dxc3 11. Qxh8+ Nf8 12. Kd1 Qa5) (5. Qh5 
{This move, known as the Haldane Attack, is also covered.}) c5 6. dxc5 (6. Bg5 
{, the Jackal Attack, is also covered.}) Nc6 {[%cal 
Gc6e5,Gd7e5,Gd7c5,Gf8c5][%csl Rc5,Re5]} 7. Bf4 Nxc5 8. Qd2 {White intends to 
castle queenside.} (8. Bd3 {We cover 3 variations in the full course.}) (8. Be2 
{We cover 2 variations in the full course.}) Be7 9. O-O-O a6 10. h4 b5 {[%cal 
Bb5b4,Gc5e4][%csl Ge4,Rc3] White is in a bit of a tricky situation. Black is 
about to gain control over the e4-square, but White doesn't want to push pawns 
on the queenside to prevent this because he has castled queenside.} 11. h5 h6 
12. Rh3 b4 13. Ne2 Ne4 $15 {[%csl Ge4,Rd2,Rf2]} *

