1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 {The Tarrasch is one of the more solid choices for 
White, so solid we had trouble making a suggestion of what to play against the 
opening.} 4. exd5 Qxd5 ({This is by far the most solid of all of the choices to 
play against the Tarrasch.} 4... cxd4 {is also very playable but not to the 
taste of many players who avoid playing with isolated pawn like the plague.}) 5. 
Ngf3 (5. dxc5 {is covered in depth with multiple variations.} Bxc5 6. Ngf3 Nf6 
7. Bc4) cxd4 6. Bc4 Qd7 {[%cal Bb8c6,Bg8f6] Why do we play Qd7? We have had this 
question a few times in the main course. 1) Because it avoids some the nastiest 
lines in the mainlines and 2) Because it adds to established theory on the 
French.} (6... Qd6 7. O-O Nf6 8. Nb3 Nc6 9. Nbxd4 Nxd4 10. Nxd4 a6 11. Re1 Qc7 
12. Bb3 Bd6 13. Nf5 Bxh2+ 14. Kh1 O-O 15. Nxg7 Rd8 16. Qf3 Kxg7 17. Bh6+ Kg6 18. 
c3 Nh5 19. Bc1 Bf4 20. g4 {With over 100 games in the database this position has 
been seen and played many times, we have tried to avoid these types of systems 
when possible to trailblaze.}) 7. O-O (7. Qe2 Nc6 8. Nb3 Nf6 9. Bd2 a6 10. O-O-O 
b5 {Typically the most aggressive variations in chess deal with castling on 
opposite wings, we dive into this position with a confident result for the 
second player.}) Nc6 8. Nb3 Nf6 9. Nbxd4 Nxd4 10. Nxd4 a6 {[%cal 
Gc4b5,Gd4b5,Bb7b5][%csl Gb5]} 11. Re1 (11. a4 Bc5 {Compared to the mainline with 
the Queen on d6 we have extra options for our good Bishop.} 12. Nb3 Bd6 13. Qe2 
Qc7 14. h3 h6) Bc5 12. c3 b5 13. Bb3 (13. Bxe6 {A sacrifice we need to be aware 
of and to understand that Black has the better of it when handled properly.} 
fxe6 14. Rxe6+ Kf8 15. Rxf6+ gxf6 16. Bh6+ Kg8 17. Qh5 Bxd4 18. cxd4 Qe6) Bb7 
14. Bg5 Bxd4 15. cxd4 Qc6 {[%cal Gb7g2][%csl Rg2]} 16. f3 O-O 17. Qd3 {[%cal 
Ba1c1,Bb3c2,Gc2h7][%csl Rh7]} (17. Rc1 Qb6 {transposes.}) Rac8 {[%cal 
Gc8c2][%csl Gc2] A precise move. We get in extra development while delaying 
White from playing Bc2.} 18. Rac1 ({If} 18. Bxf6 {, we respond like before. 
After recapturing on f6, we bring our king to h8 and our rook to g8. If needed, 
we can play ...f5 to shut down pressure on h7.}) Qb6 19. Bc2 Rfd8 {[%cal 
Gb6d4,Gd8d4,Bc8c4,Gc4d4][%csl Rd4] Black is counterattacking the d4 pawn and is 
ready to increase pressure further with ...Rc4} 20. Bxf6 gxf6 21. Qxh7+ Kf8 $10 
{[%cal Gb6g1,Gd8d4][%csl Rd4,Rg1] With a dynamically equal position.} *

