1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 {3. Nd2 is of course dealt with in the course through 
transposition.} dxe4 {Forcing things! If you do not prefer our suggestion in the 
Classical, the Tarrasch, or both... we have the Rubenstein as a trusty secondary 
system. Looking at many, many games from GM Meier on chess.com has taught us the 
resilience of this system.} 4. Nxe4 Nd7 {[%cal Bg8f6,Gf6e4]} 5. Nf3 (5. g3 {Is 
an interesting try for White.} b6 6. Bg2 Rb8 7. Qe2 Bb7 {It is not often we see 
...Rb8 to play ...Bb7. It is an efficient way to play against the strong 
g2-Bishop and activate our French Bishop.}) Ngf6 6. Nxf6+ {We investigate many 
6th move options, all of which have multiple variations and are covered in 
detial.} (6. Ng3 c5 7. Be2 Qc7 8. O-O b6 9. c4 Bb7) (6. Bg5 h6 7. Nxf6+ Nxf6 8. 
Bh4 c5 9. Bb5+ Bd7 10. Bxd7+ Qxd7 11. Qe2 Be7 12. O-O-O O-O 13. dxc5 Qa4 {The 6. 
Bg5-variation is one of the more intimidating variations we investigate quite 
carefully.}) (6. Bd3 c5 {The typical breaking moves in these variations that 
Black needs to keep in mind.}) Nxf6 7. Bd3 c5 {[%cal Gc5d4][%csl Rd4]} 8. O-O 
cxd4 9. Nxd4 Bc5 {[%cal Gc5d4,Gd8d4][%csl Rd4]} 10. Nb3 Bd6 11. Qf3 Qc7 {[%cal 
Gc7b7,Bc8d7] Al Ghamdi, Ahmed M - Meier, Geo, 0-1, World Blitz 2017. Starting 
with ...Qc7 instead of ...Bd7 because we need to keep b7 protected.} 12. h3 Bd7 
13. Nd4 {[%cal Gd4b5,Gd3b5][%csl Rb5]} a6 {[%cal Ga6b5][%csl Gb5]} 14. Re1 O-O-O 
$5 ({As in Molner, M. - Shetty, A., 0-1, 42nd World Open 2014. Black could also 
play calmly with} 14... O-O {.}) *

