1. e4 e6 2. d3 {A common move favored by many strong players throughout history, 
Fischer enjoyed it when he was young. Currently, GM Amin is one of the best 
King's Indian Attack players in the world. This opening can occur from numerous 
move orders, such as 1. Nf3. If you are a 1. d4 player this chapter will be very 
useful.} (2. Qe2 {falls under the same category as the King's Indian Attack, as 
Black can handle it the same way as long as we avoid the trap of playing 2. d5 
here.} Be7 {a key move, so that when d5 is played we have the ability to capture 
back with the e-pawn.} 3. Nf3 d5 4. d3) d5 3. Nd2 Nf6 (3... c5 {is another 
alternative we cover.} 4. Ngf3 Nc6 5. g3 Bd6 {directly plays against the idea of 
e5 for white.} 6. Bg2 Nge7 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 f6) 4. Ngf3 b6 {[%cal 
Bg2g3,Bf1g2,Bc8a6,Ga6f1][%csl Re1] An interesting move with the idea of 
exploiting the light squares unless White plays accurately.} (4... c5 {is our 
alternative line idea} 5. g3 Nc6 6. Bg2 Be7 7. O-O Qc7 {Notice that Black is not 
castling kingside here as White's typical plan is to attack on that wing. We 
have a devilish plan in store.} 8. Re1 b6 9. e5 (9. c3 {Is the much better move 
for White as it allows for a Byrne plan idea of a3 and b4 if Black elects to 
castle Queenside.} Bb7 10. a3 h6 {Both sides play the waiting game to see who 
will blink first, Black will typically castle Kingside if White plays all of 
these extra moves on the Queenside.}) 9... Nd7 10. Nf1 Bb7 11. Bf4 h6 12. h4 
O-O-O {With the idea of ...Rdg8 and ...g5, turning the tables.}) 5. g3 (5. c3 
Ba6 6. Be2 Be7 7. b4 {is analyzed in the main course.}) dxe4 6. dxe4 Bc5 {[%cal 
Bf1g2,Bc8a6,Bf6g4,Gg4f2][%csl Rf2]} 7. Bb5+ (7. Bg2 {The typical King's Indian 
development leads to issues for White:} Ba6) c6 8. Bd3 e5 ({Using tactics to get 
in ...e5 favorably.} e5 9. Nxe5 {runs into} 9... Qd4 {with a winning double 
attack on e5 and f2.}) 9. Nc4 Nbd7 10. Qe2 O-O 11. O-O Qc7 $10 {[%cal 
Bf8e8,Bd7f8] An equal middlegame has arisen and Black should feel like he has 
the moral victory here as he has forced White out of his typical structure.} *

