1. e4 e6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e5 c5 4. b4 {The Wing Gambit: This gambit is surprisingly 
viable and offers Black many chances to go wrong.} b6 {[%cal Bc8a6] We are one 
of the few authors who will openly decline the gambit and we ask readers to 
think back to our Advanced Variation notes for guidance, rid yourself of the 
French Bishop!} (4... cxb4 5. d4 Bd7 6. a3 Nc6 7. axb4 Bxb4+ 8. c3 Be7 9. Bd3 
{We could not feel strongly about many of the lines accepting the gambit, the 
plans for Black are difficult to find and White gets a ready-made attack with 
his strong good Bishop which has survived the opening.}) 5. bxc5 {Multiple tries 
by White on move 5 are covered.} (5. c3) (5. a3) bxc5 6. c3 {Preparing d2-d4 and 
stopping ...d4.} Qa5 {[%cal Bc8a6,Ga5a6]} 7. d4 Ba6 {THERE IT IS!} 8. Bxa6 Qxa6 
9. Qe2 Ne7 $10 {[%cal Be7g6,Bf8e7,Be8g8]} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: The French Defense"]
[Site "Main Level"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Rare Lines - 2 b3"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "Main Level"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-the-french-defense/course/25950, variation/4305762"]

1. e4 e6 2. b3 {Known as the Reti Variation or the Horwitz attack. White plans 
to castle long and, using the fianchettoed bishop, launch an attack with the 
g-pawn against Black's kingside. However, the b2-b3 move comes with a 
significant consequence: Black will easily open the a-file using ...a7-a5-a4 
advance. Black's development plan includes ...Bb4, ...Qe7 followed by ...Bb4-a3 
with a very fast attack against White's queenside castled king.} d5 {[%csl Re4]} 
3. Bb2 dxe4 4. Nc3 Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4,Bf8b4]} 5. g4 {We cover multiple options on 
move 5:} (5. Qe2 Bb4 6. O-O-O Qe7) (5. g3 e5 6. Bg2 Bg4) (5. Nge2 b6 6. Ng3 Bb7) 
h6 6. Bg2 Bd7 {[%cal Bd7c6,Gc6e4][%csl Ge4]} 7. Qe2 (7. Nxe4 Nxe4 8. Bxe4 Bc6 9. 
Qe2 h5) Bc6 8. O-O-O (8. Nxe4 {would transpose to the the previous Nxe4 line.}) 
a5 {[%cal Ba5a4][%csl Rc1]} 9. a3 {Preparing to play b3-b4 in response to 
...a5-a4, but this weakens the b3-pawn.} Bc5 {[%cal Bc5d4,Gd4b2][%csl Rb2] Black 
uses the d4-square to trade the dark-squares bishops.} 10. Nxe4 Bd4 11. c3 Nxe4 
12. Bxe4 Bxe4 13. Qxe4 Bxf2 {Black can get away with snagging this pawn. White 
can take the pawn on b7, but this will help us attack the queenside later.} 14. 
Nf3 Nd7 15. d4 c6 {[%cal Gc6d5,Ge6d5][%csl Gd5] It is a good idea to shut down 
any pawn central pawn advance White might contrive because our king is still in 
the center.} 16. Rd2 Bh4 $15 {[%cal Bh4f6,Bf6e7,Bh4g5] The bishop escapes.} *

