1. e4 e6 2. e5 {The Steinitz Attack. The only variation White can throw at us 
that can change our typical structure.} d5 {If 3. d4, we transpose into our 
lines in the Advance. If 3. f4, we transpose into our chapter on f4. If 3. d3, 
is an independent try from the transposition of 2. f4 lines, but leads to issues 
quickly. (See the subvariation on the next move)} 3. exd6 {The branching point.} 
(3. Nc3 c5 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nb5 Nc6 6. Nf3 Bc5 7. Nbxd4 Bxd4 8. Nxd4 Nxe5) (3. d3 
c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. c3 Nge7 6. Na3 Ng6 7. d4 cxd4 8. cxd4 Nh4) cxd6 {[%csl 
Gd6,Ge6]} ({This seems stronger and more imbalancing than the alternative with} 
3... Bxd6 {as many of the responses result in very drawish positions for 
Black.}) 4. d4 Nf6 {[%cal Bf8e7,Be8g8]} 5. Nf3 Be7 6. Bd3 O-O 7. O-O b6 {[%cal 
Bc8b7,Bb8d7]} 8. Re1 Bb7 9. Nbd2 Nbd7 10. c3 Re8 {[%cal Be7f8]} 11. Nf1 a6 
{Black adopts a hedgehog structure, which is solid, effective, and seen 
throughout many chess openings.} 12. Ng3 Bf8 13. Bg5 Qc7 14. Bxf6 Nxf6 15. Ne4 
Nd5 16. Rc1 Nf4 17. Bf1 e5 18. g3 Ng6 19. dxe5 dxe5 {[%csl Gb7,Gf8] This is 
deemed roughly equal by the engine but we feel that Black has reasonable chances 
with the Bishop pair in an open position, here improving upon Mahmut - Burak, 
0-1, 1.04.18, Basel Open.} *

