1. e4 e6 2. f4 {The Labourdonnais Variation. This is a distant cousin to the 
Advance Variation.} d5 3. e5 {There are a few options we explore on move 3.} (3. 
Nc3) (3. exd5 exd5 {With an awkward Exchange variation with the misplaced pawn 
on f4.}) Nh6 {[%cal Bh6f5,Gf5d4][%csl Gf5,Rd4] This awkward move will allow 
black to pressure the center by going to f5 in many variations.} 4. Nf3 c5 
{[%cal Gc5d4]} 5. c3 Nc6 {[%cal Gc5d4,Gc6d4]} 6. Na3 Qb6 {[%cal 
Gc6d4,Gc5d4,Gb6d4]} 7. Nc2 Bd7 8. d4 (8. d3 Be7 9. g3 f6 10. exf6 gxf6 11. Qe2 
O-O-O 12. Bh3 f5 13. Bg2 Ng4) cxd4 9. cxd4 Nf5 {[%cal Gf5d4,Gc6d4,Gb6d4][%csl 
Rd4] Full coordination against the d4-pawn. It bodes well that the c2-Knight is 
purely defensive, it feels at first glance that Black already has a little 
something.} 10. g4 Nfe7 11. Bh3 {After any other move ...h5 comes with too much 
strength for White to handle.} h5 {[%cal Ge7f5][%csl Rg4,Gf5]} 12. g5 g6 {To 
stop White from playing g6 himself.} 13. O-O a5 {This provocative move gives 
White room to go wrong in the position.} 14. Rf2 Nb4 {[%cal 
Bc2b4,Ba5b4,Ga8a1][%csl Ra2] If White captures, we capture back with the a-pawn 
with long-term pressure down the a-file.} 15. a4 Nec6 16. Bf1 Nxc2 17. Rxc2 Be7 
{[%csl Rg1,Ge8,Rd4] We have an equal position with no attack for White on the 
Kingside, in the long-term Black has the safer King and better prospects in the 
upcoming heavy piece ending.} *

